                "name": "Michael Mombourquette",
                "href": "/profile/Michael-Mombourquette"
            },
            "answer_text": "The bar of soap will retain some of the dirt that was on your hands. It will not self clean. However, it generally allows that once you are done using it, you rinse your hands which will then wash off any remaining contaminants because they are now trapped in the soap that you have on your hands. If you also rinse off the soap bar before you put it back, you can clean if off fairly well too. We use soap dispensers in our house to eliminate the need for those \u2018dirty\u2019 bars of soap. However, even these might spread contaminants as we all have to touch the same handle to pump out the soap. Some commercially supplied soap dispensers are automatic. They sense your hand and pump out a dollop of soap onto your hand without you touching anything. These are the closest to a perfect non-infecting method of supplying soap. Generally, we rely on very thorough rinsing with running water to wash off any contaminants. Ever watch a surgeon prepare for surgery? Lots of running water, very little touching of anything except sterile towels and gloves. ",
